    "recipient": "Shaq",
    "task_context": "Implement user authentication with session management (sliding 30-minute expiration) and account status enforcement. Bird defined domain rules and acceptance criteria; MJ designed the technical architecture using Redis-backed tokens. One terminology conflict between Bird and MJ requires attention before implementation — see contradictions_resolved.",
    "domain_rules": [
      {
        "rule": "A session is valid for 30 minutes from last user activity (sliding window, not fixed expiry)",
        "testable_assertion": "Any authenticated request made more than 30 minutes after the last activity on that session must return 401 SESSION_EXPIRED"
      },
      {
        "rule": "A suspended account cannot initiate a new session",
        "testable_assertion": "Login attempt by a suspended account must return 403 ACCOUNT_SUSPENDED before any token is issued"
      }
    ],
    "architecture_guidance": [
      {
        "decision": "Token storage in Redis with TTL = 1800 seconds",
        "implementation_note": "Redis TTL provides automatic cleanup of expired tokens. On each authenticated request, reset the TTL to 1800s to implement the sliding window. The TTL is the enforcement mechanism — no separate expiry-check cron needed."
      },
      {
        "decision": "Token validation middleware checks last_accessed_at",
        "implementation_note": "Middleware intercepts every authenticated request, reads the token from Redis, checks last_accessed_at against current time. If delta > 30 minutes, return 401 SESSION_EXPIRED. If valid, update last_accessed_at and reset Redis TTL."
      },
      {
        "decision": "Account status check at token issuance (login time)",
        "implementation_note": "Before issuing a token, query account status. If account is suspended/locked, reject with 403 ACCOUNT_SUSPENDED. This is a gate at login — do NOT issue a token and then check status on each request."
      }
    ],
    "acceptance_criteria": [
      {
        "criterion": "Expired session returns 401",
        "given": "An active session that has been idle for 31 minutes",
        "when": "Any authenticated request is made using that session's token",
        "then": "A 401 is returned with error code SESSION_EXPIRED"
      },
      {
        "criterion": "Suspended account cannot log in",
        "given": "An account with status suspended",
        "when": "A login attempt is made with valid credentials for that account",
        "then": "A 403 is returned with error code ACCOUNT_SUSPENDED and no token is issued"
      }
    ],
    "terminology_alignment": [
      {
        "domain_term": "session",
        "technical_term": "token (Redis-backed with TTL)",
        "definition": "A session in domain terms maps to a token in the technical layer. Each login creates a token in Redis; the token's TTL and last_accessed_at field implement the session's sliding expiration window."
      },
      {
        "domain_term": "last user activity",
        "technical_term": "last_accessed_at field on the token",
        "definition": "Each authenticated request counts as user activity. The last_accessed_at timestamp is updated on every valid request and the Redis TTL is reset."
      }
    ],
    "contradictions_resolved": [
      {
        "conflict": "TERMINOLOGY CONFLICT (unresolved): Bird uses 'suspended account' as the domain term; MJ uses 'locked' as the account status. These may refer to the same concept or to distinct account states (e.g., 'suspended' = admin action, 'locked' = too many failed login attempts). This must be clarified before implementation.",
        "resolution": "Routed to Bird for alignment. Shaq MUST NOT implement until Bird confirms whether 'suspended' and 'locked' are synonyms or distinct states. If synonyms, pick one canonical term and use it everywhere. If distinct, Bird must provide separate domain rules and acceptance criteria for each state."
      }
    ],
    "open_questions": [
      "What is the canonical account status field name — 'suspended' (Bird) or 'locked' (MJ)? Are these the same state or two different states with different business meanings?",
      "Should the system also check account status on each authenticated request (not just at login)? If an account is suspended mid-session, should existing tokens be invalidated immediately?",
      "What error code format is expected — string enum (SESSION_EXPIRED) or numeric? MJ did not specify; Bird's ACs use string codes."
    ]
  },
